        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.altdaily.co/email/images/an-dec-25-3.jpg" alt="chart" href="https://www.altdaily.co" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
         Venture capital funds launched in 2021 and 2022 are underperforming compared to previous years. The median internal rate of return (IRR) for 2021 funds remains negative, while their median distribution to paid-in capital (DPI) is just 9%, less than half of the 2017-2019 vintages. This underperformance stems from funds deploying capital during 2021’s overheated market, which saw record exits ($797 billion) and VC funding ($128.3 billion).</p>
         <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
         However, valuations and exit volumes plummeted from 2022 onwards due to rising interest rates, forcing many startups into down rounds. Established firms that benefited from 2021’s high exits can weather this, but first-time funds are struggling, potentially jeopardizing their ability to raise future investments.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
   

