          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Swiss PE shifts focus in India after gains:</strong>   
         Partners Group, a Swiss private equity firm, is <a href="https://link.altdaily.co/ad-25-dec-2024-3-reshuffling" target="_blank">reshuffling</a> its India portfolio, now valued at over $8 billion—a 300% gain over the past decade. Recent exits include a $3 billion sale of a 23% stake in Vishal Mega Mart and plans to sell a 10.8% stake in Aavas Financiers for $164 million. The firm also plans a partial stake sale in logistics giant Ecom Express following the approval of its IPO draft. Proceeds will be reinvested in healthcare, AI-driven technology, education, and shadow lending in India.</p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>China IPO rules challenge private equity exits:</strong>   
         Tighter IPO regulations and a slowing economy have <a href="https://link.altdaily.co/ad-25-dec-2024-4-trapped" target="_blank">trapped</a> foreign private equity capital in China, with major firms like Blackstone and KKR struggling to exit investments. Since 2021, when Beijing restricted overseas IPOs, the 10 largest global PE firms operating in China have had no major exits. Domestic IPOs also fell sharply, raising just $7 billion in 2024 compared to $46 billion in 2022. Some PE firms are pursuing alternative exits, like domestic sales, but geopolitical tensions and regulatory hurdles persist. With over $137 billion invested in China since 2013 but only $38 billion in exits, the outlook remains uncertain.</p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>MetLife acquires PineBridge for $1.2 billion:</strong>   
         MetLife Investment Management is <a href="https://link.altdaily.co/ad-25-dec-2024-5-acquiring" target="_blank">acquiring</a> PineBridge Investments from Pacific Century Group in a deal worth up to $1.2 billion. The transaction includes $800 million in upfront cash, with $200 million tied to 2025 financial targets and an additional $20 million through earnouts. PineBridge, originally AIG’s asset management arm, excludes its private equity funds group and China JV from the deal.</p>
          </mj-text>

