        <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>TCI founder takes $242m pay cut:
         </strong> 
         Chris Hohn, founder of TCI Fund Management, saw his <a href="https://link.altdaily.co/ad-25-dec-2024-6-earnings-cut" target="_blank">earnings cut</a> by $242m in 2024, from $287m last year to $53m. Despite the pay cut, TCI significantly increased its charitable donations, contributing $427m in 2024—five times its 2023 figure. Known for its activist investing, TCI manages $57bn in assets and holds stakes in major companies like Alphabet and Microsoft. Hohn’s lifetime donations exceed $4bn, earning him the title of “the UK’s most generous man” in 2023.</p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Hedge funds ramp up crude oil bets:
        </strong> Hedge funds have increased <a href="https://link.altdaily.co/ad-25-dec-2024-7-bullish-bets" target="_blank">bullish bets</a> on crude oil, with WTI long positions rising by over 57,000 contracts—the largest increase since September 2023. This shift is driven by potential sanctions on Russian and Iranian oil and stronger-than-expected stimulus from China, the world’s largest crude importer. WTI prices have surged, aligning closely with Brent, which also saw a rise in bullish positions.</p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Pershing Square expands buybacks to $200M:
         </strong> 
         Pershing Square Holdings, led by Bill Ackman, has <a href="https://link.altdaily.co/ad-25-dec-2024-8-doubled" target="_blank">doubled</a> its share buyback program to $200 million to address a persistent 34% discount on its shares. This follows a previous $100 million buyback initiated in November. Since 2017, Pershing Square has repurchased $1.4 billion worth of shares, aiming to boost NAV per share and narrow the discount. However, critics argue the increased buyback is modest at just 1.3% of net assets. The trust’s portfolio includes top holdings like Alphabet and Canadian Pacific Kansas City. Despite delivering five-year returns of 174%, recent underperformance against the S&P 500 has widened the share discount.</p>
        </mj-text>


