      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

    <mj-section css-class="mj_section" background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="             
              font-size: 20px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">What risks does shadow banking pose to emerging markets?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.altdaily.co/email/images/an-dec-25-4.jpg" alt="foundations" href="https://www.altdaily.co" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          Shadow banking, which includes non-bank financial intermediaries like hedge funds, private equity firms, and microfinance institutions, plays an essential role in providing credit, particularly in emerging markets with limited traditional banking access. However, it comes with significant risks. One major concern is the lack of transparency. Unlike commercial banks, shadow banks are not subject to the same level of regulatory oversight, making it difficult to monitor their activities or measure their exposure to risks. This opacity leaves regulators and investors unaware of the potential vulnerabilities these entities could introduce to the financial system.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          Another risk lies in their reliance on short-term funding sources. If lenders suddenly withdraw their funds, shadow banks may face liquidity crises, forcing them to sell assets rapidly, which can destabilize markets. Furthermore, their involvement in complex, high-risk financial products amplifies credit risks, often underestimated or poorly understood. Given the interconnectedness of financial markets, disruptions in the shadow banking system can trigger ripple effects, leading to broader systemic crises. For emerging markets, these risks are particularly acute, as such economies may lack the resilience to absorb shocks originating from shadow banking failures.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
